WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:04.480
Welcome to Part 2 of my Blender Tutorial&nbsp;
on material shading. If you stumbled across&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:09.360
this video first, there is a Part 1 that covers&nbsp;
the absolute basics of shading in Blender. Part&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:13.840
2 is all about PBR materials. What they are,&nbsp;
where you get them and how to set them up.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:16.720
With a bunch of extra tips&nbsp;
along the way and at the end.&nbsp;

00:00:16.720 --> 00:00:21.040
I will be using Cycles for this tutorial. Most&nbsp;
of this will work in Eevee too so let’s go.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:24.640
The PBR in “PBR materials” stands&nbsp;
for Physically Based Rendering.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:29.520
It’s a workflow for using physical information&nbsp;
- images - to generate textures. You could make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:33.120
your own PBR textures, but don’t because&nbsp;
there are tons of them already out there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:38.080
PBR textures are generally going to look much more&nbsp;
realistic than procedural textures which are made&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:42.480
by combining inputs like we did in part one.
When you obtain a PBR texture, you’re going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:47.680
get a series of images with specific labels. Each&nbsp;
image controls a different effect of the material.&nbsp;

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:52.560
So where do you get PBR materials? Lots of&nbsp;
places. I often use Poliigon which has both&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:56.080
free and paid materials. I’ve been happy&nbsp;
with them and will include an affiliate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.080 --> 00:01:00.240
link in the description. But, there are other&nbsp;
places to get free PBR materials for Blender.&nbsp;

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:04.720
Ambient CG is one place I would check out, but I’m&nbsp;
going to be using Poliigon. You can see they have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:09.920
a pretty large library of really good materials.
When you choose a PBR material, also referred to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:15.680
as a PBR texture, you have different resolution&nbsp;
options. For example here, we have from 1K all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:22.000
the way up to 16K. Poliigon uses PNG images, but&nbsp;
some sites have JPEG’s which are smaller files but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.800
can be lower quality. Which size you choose will&nbsp;
generally be based on how far away the material&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:30.880
is going to be in your scene. For things in the&nbsp;
background and honestly for most of your scene,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:36.240
1K is probably fine. If it’s going to be close up&nbsp;
to the camera, consider going up a size or two.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.240 --> 00:01:40.800
Generally I find 3K to be fine for almost&nbsp;
anything. The larger the resolution,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.840
the more it adds to memory draw and render time.
These are all the different maps the texture comes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:50.800
with. I know I won’t use all of them, in fact&nbsp;
the two bump maps and two displacement maps are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:55.760
just different size options you can use with this&nbsp;
material. But they don’t cost any extra, so I’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.760 --> 00:02:00.880
just download them all. They’ll all download into&nbsp;
a zip file which you can unzip on your computer.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:05.920
It’s generally a good idea to store all of your&nbsp;
PBR textures in an organized file system. You can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:10.240
change the names of the folders but don’t rename&nbsp;
the actual images themselves. They’re named the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:13.840
way they are so that they can be recognized&nbsp;
by certain addons which we’ll see later.&nbsp;

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:19.280
Let’s go back into Blender and just start with&nbsp;
a new plane with a new material. I’ll name it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:24.960
Poliigon, then let’s go into the shader editor.
We’ve got our default Principled BSDF shader.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:30.160
I also have the file folder open with&nbsp;
the files I downloaded from Poliigon.com.&nbsp;

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:34.000
We can bring these files into the shader&nbsp;
editor a number of ways. We could press&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.800
Shift+A and add an image texture. This is&nbsp;
the node that plugs images into your node&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:43.360
tree. We can press “open” and navigate to&nbsp;
the folder where the material files are.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:49.360
Or, if we have the folder open, we can simply&nbsp;
drag and drop an image into the shader editor.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:52.960
Blender will automatically add&nbsp;
it into an image texture node.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:58.080
A side note, you can navigate to and open these&nbsp;
image files even if they’re not extracted. But,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:02.880
dragging and dropping the files won’t work unless&nbsp;
you extract the zip file. That’s good to know.

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:06.800
The first file we are going to start with is the&nbsp;
one labeled “color.” Actually, there are different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:10.960
variations provided with this material. These are&nbsp;
just slightly different color options you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:15.520
with this material. I’ll pick one and I’ll drag&nbsp;
it into Blender. Since this is our base color,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:19.760
we are going to drag the color output (the&nbsp;
yellow) into the base color input of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:24.080
Principled shader (which is also yellow).&nbsp;
Now, we’ve got our PBR base color laid out.

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:25.760
If you’ve made it this far,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:28.880
please hit that like button - it would&nbsp;
mean the world to me. Thank you so much!

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:33.680
Next we’re going to work on our specular&nbsp;
input. Remember in part one I said there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:37.840
are two workflows, specular and metallic.
Let me just go back to Poliigon for a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:41.600
second. For certain metal materials,&nbsp;
you’ll see an option for workflow.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:46.480
You can choose “metalness” or specular. These are&nbsp;
the two workflows I mentioned in part 1. There&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:51.520
are different reasons to use each one, it seems&nbsp;
metalness is more popular for metal materials.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:55.680
Either one you want to use is fine, it’ll&nbsp;
just change one map that you have to plug in.&nbsp;

00:03:55.680 --> 00:04:00.160
But for materials that are not metal, you won’t&nbsp;
see a metalness map and you’ll use a specular&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:06.080
map. But notice we don’t have an image labeled&nbsp;
specular here either. Sometimes specular maps&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:10.640
are called “reflection” maps. We do have&nbsp;
a map labeled “reflection” and that’s the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:14.640
one we’re going to use right here. Drag the&nbsp;
reflection map into Blender and connect it to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:20.240
the specular socket. Reflection equals specular.
Now, we have an issue here. We just plugged a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:25.360
yellow socket into a grey socket. This isn’t the&nbsp;
end of the world, but when using an image texture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:30.880
but NOT using it for color data, we need&nbsp;
to change this drop down box from “sRGB”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:36.080
which means color, to “non-color.” This tells&nbsp;
Blender that even though this is a yellow output,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:40.560
it’s not putting out color information with&nbsp;
this particular map. The end result will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:44.640
usually be just a little off if you don’t&nbsp;
change this setting for non-color maps.

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:49.280
There’s one step we’ve missed here though.&nbsp;
And that is the mapping we covered in part 1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:53.840
We want to make sure these image maps are being&nbsp;
mapped properly to the object. We need to add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.840 --> 00:04:58.320
both a mapping node and a texture coordinate&nbsp;
node. Luckily, since we have the node wrangler&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.320 --> 00:05:02.480
addon activated, there’s a shortcut. Select&nbsp;
one of the image textures and press “Control+T”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:07.200
and it automatically adds both nodes.&nbsp;
And it told the texture coordinate node&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:12.400
to use the UV mapping which is what we want.
I will very quickly explain UV’s. When we take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:16.880
a 2 dimensional texture and place it on a 3&nbsp;
dimensional object, we need to essentially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:21.680
unwrap the object. Imagine printing a&nbsp;
label directly onto a cylindrical soda can.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:26.560
UV unwrapping would be like cutting the soda&nbsp;
can open to lay it out flat so that a printer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:32.480
can print on it. The U and the V represent the 2&nbsp;
axes of the 2 dimensional texture because the 3D&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:38.000
object already has the X, Y and Z axes labeled.
Unwrapping a plane is pretty much unnecessary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.200
but it’s absolutely necessary for more complex&nbsp;
objects. To unwrap an object, we go into edit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:47.520
mode, select what we want to unwrap. (You&nbsp;
CAN unwrap different parts separately).&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:52.320
Go to UV at the top and there are actually&nbsp;
different ways to unwrap an object. Usually,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:56.880
I recommend “Smart UV Project.” Select&nbsp;
that. It has some options. Normally you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:01.520
don’t have to change anything. Press OK.
We don’t actually need to do this here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:07.600
but if you wanted to edit your UV map, you can go&nbsp;
to the UV Editing workspace. This is our UV. It’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:12.800
a very, very simple UV, but a UV nonetheless.&nbsp;
There are plenty of Blender tutorials for UV&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:17.840
unwrapping, this was just the bare minimum to&nbsp;
understand. So let’s go back to our shader editor.&nbsp;

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:22.160
So this color image is mapped through the&nbsp;
mapping node and this specular map is not.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:26.160
We want to connect this mapping node&nbsp;
to the specular map as well. Remember&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:32.000
an output can go to multiple inputs, but only&nbsp;
one output can go into a single input socket.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.720
Back to our material files, the next thing we&nbsp;
want to map is our roughness. But again, there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:42.480
is no map labeled roughness. It’s because other&nbsp;
softwares use “gloss” maps instead of roughness -&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:46.880
so you don’t always get a roughness map. But it’s&nbsp;
ok, I’ll show you how to work with this gloss map.&nbsp;

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:52.640
Let’s drag the gloss map into the shader editor.&nbsp;
We will again change “sRGB” to “non-color” because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:56.880
this isn’t providing color information to the&nbsp;
Principled Shader. It’s providing black and white&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.880 --> 00:07:01.360
data. And we’ll also connect it to the mapping&nbsp;
node. All of the image textures we use will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:05.440
get plugged into the same mapping node because&nbsp;
we need them to all line up with one another.&nbsp;

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:09.520
Now when we connect this gloss map to the&nbsp;
roughness socket, we see a noticeable difference&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:13.840
in the material - that is if we’re in render&nbsp;
preview mode. A roughness map will make a material&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:18.480
look more realistic. But there’s a problem&nbsp;
because the gloss map is actually the inverse&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:23.920
of a roughness map. What’s black on a gloss map is&nbsp;
white on the roughness map and vice versa. So the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:28.400
parts that are supposed to be rough are not rough&nbsp;
and the parts that are not supposed to be rough&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:33.760
are rough. To fix this there’s a handy node we can&nbsp;
add between the gloss map and the roughness input&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:39.520
that flips this all around. It’s called an invert&nbsp;
node. Shift+A and search for “invert” Drop this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:45.120
right between the two nodes. This node takes data&nbsp;
in from the left - like all nodes do. It flips,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:49.600
or inverts, the black and white values. Then&nbsp;
it spits out the new information on the right.

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:54.320
There’s another map in this pack that will add&nbsp;
a lot of realism. And that’s the normal map.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:59.760
Normal maps, as mentioned in part 1, fake depth&nbsp;
by manipulating how light hits the material.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:02.960
They are not very draining on your&nbsp;
computer but add enough realism to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:05.600
be used as long as they’re not&nbsp;
right up in front of the camera.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:09.760
The normal map is this purple map. It’s&nbsp;
a specific type of color mapping that I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:14.720
don’t fully understand but that Blender does. So&nbsp;
let’s drop the normal map into the shader editor.&nbsp;

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:20.080
We again need to connect this to our mapping node&nbsp;
and we again need to change it to non-color data.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:25.600
This normal map needs to be plugged into the&nbsp;
normal input of the principled shader. But look,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:30.240
we have a different problem here. We have a&nbsp;
yellow going into a purple and that’s a no-no.&nbsp;

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:36.720
So what we drop between these nodes is a normal&nbsp;
map node. Shift+A and search for normal map. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.720 --> 00:08:41.520
node takes yellow socket color information and&nbsp;
turns it into a purple output specifically for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:47.040
normal maps. This is the strength of the normal&nbsp;
map. Let’s click on it and change it to ten to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:52.480
really emphasize what this normal map is doing.
Boom. Did you see that? How much realism the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:56.800
normal map added when we turned the strength&nbsp;
up. This is one area where these materials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.800 --> 00:09:00.880
work a lot better in Cycles than they do in&nbsp;
Eevee. If we turned this strength up in Eevee,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:05.600
it really won’t do anything. Cycles is just&nbsp;
much more capable of handling details like this.

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:11.520
A quick break because Youtube pays me practically&nbsp;
nothing for these videos. Topaz Studio is one of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:16.080
my favorite tools to use after I render in&nbsp;
Bleder. It’s a collection of very powerful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:20.640
filters. I use it on every single render. Here’s&nbsp;
an example of a render straight out of Blender&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:24.880
and here’s what it looked like after using&nbsp;
Topaz Studio. I am not sponsored but I made an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:28.640
entire video on Topaz Studio and have an&nbsp;
affiliate link in the description. There&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:31.680
are endless adjustments you can make&nbsp;
to improve your render and the best&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:34.800
part - it’s a one time purchase&nbsp;
with no ongoing subscription.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:38.400
Please support my channel by checking it out with&nbsp;
the affiliate link in the description. Thank you!

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:44.800
Displacement maps in Blender give you another&nbsp;
level of realism. I’m going to turn down the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:50.400
normal value to demonstrate this. We can drag&nbsp;
the displacement map into the scene, change it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:55.120
to non-color data because it’s not going into&nbsp;
a color socket. We also want to map this to our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.120 --> 00:10:00.240
UV by connecting it to the mapping node. Now, this&nbsp;
map is going to run into the displacement channel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:04.160
not the surface channel like the others.
If we drag it directly into the displacement&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:07.920
channel, it’s not going to work because&nbsp;
we have a yellow going into a purple.&nbsp;

00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:12.320
Similar to the normal map, we need a specific&nbsp;
converter to change the information from this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:17.760
greyscale image into the information Blender needs&nbsp;
to make this displacement work. This time we are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:22.800
going to use a displacement node and drop it&nbsp;
between the displacement map and the final output&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:22.800 --> 00:10:27.920
shader. But, this automatically plugs the input&nbsp;
into the normal socket. We actually want this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:32.400
image, with black and white color information,&nbsp;
to affect the height of the displacement - not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.400 --> 00:10:36.480
the normal because it isn’t a normal map.
To actually see the changes for this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:40.400
we need to be in render preview mode.&nbsp;
They won’t show up in material preview.&nbsp;

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:44.880
When we plug the displacement into the socket,&nbsp;
a couple things happen. We do see more detail&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:49.840
in the “bump” of the material. Also, you might&nbsp;
have noticed the entire object kind of shifted.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:54.400
The shifting is because of this midlevel&nbsp;
setting. It offsets the entire geometry and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:58.560
most of the time, I’ve found I don’t want&nbsp;
it to do that so I change this to zero.&nbsp;

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:03.760
Ok, this added a little bit of bump but what’s the&nbsp;
big deal? Well, to really show you the power of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:09.200
displacement, I’m going to duplicate this plane.&nbsp;
Let’s go to the material panel and scroll down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:14.320
until we see the settings tab. Open settings and&nbsp;
under surface, we find a setting for displacement.&nbsp;

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:18.560
This setting tells Blender how to use&nbsp;
this displacement map either as a true&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:18.560 --> 00:11:23.040
displacement map or something called a bump&nbsp;
map - which is similar to a normal map as far&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:27.520
as the end result. There’s also an option to&nbsp;
use both bump and displacement which is going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:32.320
to give you the most realistic effect probably.
What it defaults to is the bump map, which is what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:38.400
we see here, a little more detail without any more&nbsp;
geometry needed. Let’s change to displacement.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:43.040
Nothing really happens. This is because true&nbsp;
displacement uses the geometry of the mesh&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:47.120
and this plane only has one face on it.&nbsp;
Let’s select this plane, tab into edit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:52.080
mode and subdivide the plane a few times.
Now when we tab into object mode we see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:57.280
the displacement has done something but this is&nbsp;
not right. On the displacement node, this scale&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.280 --> 00:12:02.080
setting affects how strong the displacement is&nbsp;
and the default of one is just way too high.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:07.280
Changing it to .1 is probably more appropriate.
But it’s still not great because we only have so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:12.800
much geometry here. Adding a subdvision surface&nbsp;
modifier will help and we should change it from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:17.200
catmull to simple because we don’t need&nbsp;
the smoothing that the catmull provides,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:21.680
just the geometry. This is alright. There&nbsp;
are a couple ways to make it better. We could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:21.680 --> 00:12:26.240
use more subdivisions or a higher resolution&nbsp;
displacement map. But realize that now we are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:30.960
significantly impacting the performance. We’ve&nbsp;
added a ton of geometry to this plane already.&nbsp;

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:36.880
The absolute best way to do this is actually&nbsp;
to use adaptive subdivision. And I fear this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:41.440
section of the tutorial is already dragging&nbsp;
on way too long. But, adaptive subdivision is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:46.320
intelligent subdivision that subdivides the&nbsp;
mesh more the closer it is to the camera&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:50.240
and it’s perfect for this. To use it, you&nbsp;
have to be in cycles, you have to turn on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:53.840
“experimental” in the render settings and&nbsp;
then on your subdivision surface, you’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:58.080
have an option for adaptive subdivision. Check&nbsp;
that and you’re going to have this displacement&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:01.920
be about as realistic as you can get it.
For a lot of things, normal maps and bump&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:05.840
maps are going to be just fine but this&nbsp;
was an overview of displacement for you.

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:10.480
Hey, remember to hit that like button&nbsp;
if you’re still here. Thank you so much!

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:16.480
Ok, so we’ve just created a basic PBR texture.&nbsp;
Let’s say this texture was either too big or too&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:21.280
small for what we wanted. We can go back to our&nbsp;
mapping node and adjust the scale. We generally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:26.560
want to adjust the scale uniformly across all&nbsp;
axes. It’d be annoying to have to adjust all three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:31.120
of these values so we can do one of two things.
Under scale, either click the top value and drag&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:31.120 --> 00:13:35.920
down. This will allow you to type in a number on&nbsp;
the top and have it applied to all three numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.920 --> 00:13:41.520
Or what I prefer to do is Shift+A and add a&nbsp;
value node. Plug it into the scale of the input.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:46.400
And now you can slide the value of this up and&nbsp;
down or type in a value. The larger the scale,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:50.240
the smaller the texture gets and it will&nbsp;
eventually start to repeat. Smaller scale&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:50.240 --> 00:13:54.880
will make the texture bigger on the object.
But, understand that we may have this texture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:59.760
applied to multiple objects and making it bigger&nbsp;
or smaller right here will change the settings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:03.840
on every object that is using this material.&nbsp;
So an alternative, and probably the way you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:09.200
should do it, is to go into the UV editor and&nbsp;
adjust the scale of the object’s UV instead.&nbsp;

00:14:09.200 --> 00:14:12.800
This on the left is our UV for what&nbsp;
we have selected. In this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:17.440
it’s the entire object’s mesh. We can press&nbsp;
“A” to make sure everything is selected.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:22.800
Then press “S” to scale the UV instead of the&nbsp;
actual material. This will only affect the scale&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.800 --> 00:14:27.760
of the material on this object and actually only&nbsp;
on the portion of the object you have selected.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:32.080
Pressing G will allow you to move it around&nbsp;
if you want to line it up how you want.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:36.880
And R will let you rotate the UV - again&nbsp;
not affecting the actual material itself.

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:41.920
That was a ton of work just to set up&nbsp;
one PBR. And it was a lot to remember.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.920 --> 00:14:46.320
Well it’s important that you got a basic&nbsp;
understanding of PBR material setups,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:51.120
but you don’t need to do this every single time&nbsp;
you set up a new material in Blender. Let’s remove&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:51.120 --> 00:14:55.520
this material and start from scratch with a new&nbsp;
Principled shader. This is only going to work&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:55.520 --> 00:15:00.240
with node wrangler activated in the preferences,&nbsp;
which we discussed in part 1 but as a reminder,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:04.720
make sure you go into your preferences - addons&nbsp;
and check on the box next to “node wrangler.”&nbsp;

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:10.960
Select the Principled BSDF shader by clicking&nbsp;
on it. Press “Control Shift T” and this file&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:16.080
navigator opens. Navigate to the folder where&nbsp;
your PBR texture files are. Select the maps&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:21.040
that you want to add. I’ll choose color,&nbsp;
gloss, reflection, normal and displacement.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:26.480
Press Principled Texture Setup.
Amazing. Blender just added all these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:31.360
maps into the shader editor and connected them&nbsp;
exactly as I already showed you how to before.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:31.360 --> 00:15:35.200
It even organized the textures into&nbsp;
frames and added a reroute node.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:40.000
It inverted the gloss and added the normal map.&nbsp;
It changed the appropriate image textures to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:45.120
non-color for us. Super easy. And that’s&nbsp;
really how you add PBR materials in Blender.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.640
And as I promised, here are a few extra tips as&nbsp;
a reward for making it this far in the video.

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:55.040
Once you have your PBR texture set up, there&nbsp;
are a few common but optional things you can do.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:58.080
For some of these black and white&nbsp;
nodes like roughness and specular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:02.480
you can feed them through a colorramp node. This&nbsp;
will give you some control over how reflective the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:07.040
material is by either sliding the control points&nbsp;
or darkening the white values. You could put them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:11.120
through separate colorramp nodes or through a&nbsp;
single node to control both of them together.&nbsp;

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:14.720
When you have color information traveling&nbsp;
from one node to another, there are a few&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:14.720 --> 00:16:19.040
nodes that you can actually use to adjust the&nbsp;
colors. Let’s first start with a hue/saturation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:23.680
node and plug it in here. Changing the hue&nbsp;
could give a stylized look to the material.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:28.800
The saturation setting can add saturation to&nbsp;
the base color or lower it to have a more black&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:33.680
and white look. And with the value slider, you&nbsp;
can lower the value to make the material darker&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:37.840
or increase it to make it lighter.
With any node selected, you can press&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:37.840 --> 00:16:42.560
“M” on your keyboard to mute the node. This&nbsp;
removes all of that node’s calculations without&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:42.560 --> 00:16:47.360
having to remove the node itself. It’s a good way&nbsp;
to quickly see if you prefer the material with or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:51.840
without the changes made by this node.
Another node you can add here is an RGB&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:56.480
curves node. You may or may not be familiar&nbsp;
with using curves for color correction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.480 --> 00:17:00.720
but in short there’s a red, green and blue&nbsp;
channel as well as a combined channel that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:04.640
controls all of them at once. There’s&nbsp;
an entire science behind using curves to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:09.680
adjust colors if you wanted to look into that.
These reroute nodes are handy when you have one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:09.680 --> 00:17:14.880
output going to multiple inputs. You can add one&nbsp;
by pressing Shift+A and searching for “reroute.”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:18.880
Or if your nodes are already connected&nbsp;
and you have node wrangler turned on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:23.520
you can hold down shift, click and drag across&nbsp;
the multiple connections and Blender will add&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:28.160
a reroute node for you. If you want to move the&nbsp;
reroute node, you need to select it and press G&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:32.400
to move it round like you would with an object.
If you want these nodes to take up less space,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:37.360
you can click this expand arrow at the top left&nbsp;
of a node, to collapse it down to just this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:41.200
It removes clutter but you can quickly&nbsp;
expand it back out when you need it.&nbsp;

00:17:41.200 --> 00:17:46.000
When you have a big node like the Principled&nbsp;
BSDF, but you’re not using all of the sockets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.880
you can select the node and go to Node - Toggle&nbsp;
Hidden Node Sockets (or you can press Control+H)&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:56.000
and it hides the sockets you’re not using.
These connections, that are also called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.280
“noodles” by the way in Blender. You&nbsp;
can control how straight or curvy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:03.120
they are. I think they might actually be&nbsp;
straight by default but I don’t remember.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:03.120 --> 00:18:09.680
Go to edit - preferences - themes - then find node&nbsp;
editor and expand this part. Go all the way down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:14.560
to the bottom and there’s a setting called “noodle&nbsp;
curving.” I have it set to four. Changing it to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:19.280
zero will make the noodles completely straight.&nbsp;
Increasing it will change the curviness of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:23.600
noodle, you can adjust to your own liking.
My name is Brandon, don’t forget to hit that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.600 --> 00:18:27.360
like button and subscribe if you haven’t&nbsp;
already. Thank you so much for watching!

